<section xml:id="section-matrix-ops-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title><term><m>\nth[(i,j)]</m> entry of a matrix</term></title>
	<idx><h>entry (of a matrix)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>entry</h></idx>
	<p>the entry in the <m>\nth[i]</m> row and <m>\nth[j]</m> column of a matrix</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>size (or dimensions) of a matrix</term></title>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>size</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>dimensions</h></idx>
	<idx><h>size (of a matrix)</h></idx>
	<p>the number of rows and columns in a matrix, usually written <m>m \times n</m> to mean <m>m</m> rows and <m>n</m> columns</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>equal matrices</term></title>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>equality</h></idx>
	<p>matrices with the same size, and the same numbers in corresponding entries</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>matrix addition</term></title>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>addition</h></idx>
	<idx><h>addition</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<p>the new matrix obtained from two old matrices of identical sizes by adding corresponding entries</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>scalar multiple</term></title>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>scalar multiple</h></idx>
	<idx><h>scalar</h><h>multiple</h><h>of a matrix</h></idx>
	<p>
	the new matrix obtained from an old matrix obtained by multiplying every entry by the same number <m>k</m>; the common <term>scale factor</term> <m>k</m> is called a <term>scalar</term><idx><h>scalar</h></idx>
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<remark><p>
	We will encounter the geometric origin of the word <term>scalar</term> in
	<xref ref="chapter-vectors" />.
</p></remark>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title><term>zero matrix</term></title>
	<idx><h>zero</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>zero</h></idx>
	<p>a matrix where every entry is zero, written <m>\zerovec</m></p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>column vector</term></title>
	<idx><h>column</h><h>vector</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>column</h></idx>
	<p>a matrix consisting of a single column</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>row vector</term></title>
	<idx><h>row</h><h>vector</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>row</h></idx>
	<p>a matrix consisting of a single row</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>vector of unknowns</term></title>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>of unknowns</h></idx>
	<p>a column vector containing all of the variables in a system</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>vector of constants</term></title>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>of constants</h></idx>
	<p>a column vector containing all of the constants from the right-hand sides of the equations in a system</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>square matrix</term></title>
	<idx><h>square matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>square</h></idx>
	<p>a matrix with the same number of columns as rows</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>main diagonal</term></title> <!-- used in this chapter in discussion of the transpose -->
	<idx><h>main diagonal</h></idx>
	<p>the diagonal of entries in a square matrix from top left to bottom right</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>transpose</term></title>
	<idx><h>transpose</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>transpose</h></idx>
	<p>the new matrix obtained from an old matrix by turning rows into columns and columns into rows; we usually write <m>\utrans{A}</m> to mean the transpose of the matrix <m>A</m></p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
